    "innerHtml": "Warren's Address To The American Soldiers."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "There is never a boy who objects to learning \"Warren's Address,\" by John Pierpont (1785-1866). To stand by one's own rights is inherent in every true American. This poem is doubtless developed from Robert Burns's \"Bannockburn.\" (1785-1866.)"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>Stand! the ground's your own, my braves!  \nWill ye give it up to slaves?  \nWill ye look for greener graves?  \nHope ye mercy still?  \nWhat's the mercy despots feel?  \nHear it in that battle-peal!  \nRead it on yon bristling steel!  \nAsk it,—ye who will.  \n\nFear ye foes who kill for hire?  \nWill ye to your homes retire?  \nLook behind you! they're afire!  \nAnd, before you, see  \nWho have done it!—From the vale  \nOn they come!—And will ye quail?—  \nLeaden rain and iron hail  \nLet their welcome be!  \n\nIn the God of battles trust!  \nDie we may,—and die we must;  \nBut, O, where can dust to dust  \nBe consigned so well,  \nAs where Heaven its dews shall shed  \nOn the martyred patriot's bed,  \nAnd the rocks shall raise their head,  \nOf his deeds to tell!  </code>"
  },
