  {
    "tag": "h3",
    "innerHtml": "On His Blindness."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "\"Sonnet on His Blindness\" (by John Milton, 1608-74). This is the most stately and pathetic sonnet in existence. The soul enduring enforced idleness and loss of power without repining. Inactivity made to serve a higher end."
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>\"All service ranks the same with God!  \nThere is no first or last.\"  </p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "<code>When I consider how my light is spent  \nEre half my days, in this dark world and wide,  \nAnd that one talent which is death to hide,  \nLodg'd with me useless, though my soul more bent  \nTo serve therewith my Maker, and present  \nMy true account, lest He, returning, chide;  \nDoth God exact day-labour, light denied?  \nI fondly ask: but Patience, to prevent  \nThat murmur, soon replies, God doth not need  \nEither man's work, or His own gifts; who best  \nBear His mild yoke, they serve Him best; His state  \nIs kingly; thousands at His bidding speed,  \nAnd post o'er land and ocean without rest;  \nThey also serve who only stand and wait.</code>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "-John Milton."
